        '**Unified platform over multiple tools:** Decided to consolidate fragmented tools (manual checklists, spreadsheets, licensed BI tool) into single integrated platform. *Problem:* Fragmentation caused 55% data completeness, inconsistent workflows, $5M+ TCO. *Alternatives:* Improve existing tools separately (does not solve fragmentation), consolidate gradually (delayed ROI), build unified platform (chosen). *Why:* Unified system ensures consistency, reduces tool-switching friction, enables cross-layer insights (employee → executive). *Impact:* Achieved **$11.5M total savings** ($6.5M operational + $5M TCO) and **55% → 95% data completeness**.',
        '**Gamification for employee workflows over standard checklists:** Designed scoring system with daily/weekly goals instead of basic task lists. *Problem:* Employees lacked motivation to complete routine tasks — only 65% adherence. *Alternatives:* Standard checklists (low engagement), mandatory enforcement (creates resentment), gamification with scoring (chosen). *Why:* Positive reinforcement drives intrinsic motivation better than mandates — visible progress and peer comparison encourage completion. *Impact:* Increased adherence by **+30% (65% → 95%)** through behavioral design.',
        '**Multi-level BI dashboards (role-specific views) over universal dashboard:** Created 3 distinct dashboard experiences for employees, managers, and executives instead of one-size-fits-all. *Problem:* Different roles need different data depth — employees need tasks, managers need alerts, executives need trends. *Alternatives:* Universal dashboard with filters (overwhelming), separate apps (fragmentation), role-based views in one platform (chosen). *Why:* Role-specific experiences prevent information overload while enabling drill-down when needed. *Impact:* **92% user satisfaction** and **40-60% faster reporting** by matching data to role needs.',
        '**Localization-first architecture over post-launch adaptation:** Designed system with localization baked into IA, not as afterthought. *Problem:* Global rollout to APAC/EMEA requires language/regional customization — retrofitting is expensive. *Alternatives:* Build for one market first (causes redesign), plan for localization later (technical debt), localization-first (chosen). *Why:* Early planning prevents structural changes and reduces long-term cost. *Impact:* Enabled seamless rollout to **10,000+ users across 8 markets** without major redesigns.'
